      "type": "developer-platform",
      "headline": "PayPal refreshes Invoicing API docs for create, send, manage, reminder, and refund flows",
      "buyerRelevance": "Buyers embedding invoicing into their own app can evaluate PayPal as an API-backed invoicing layer, not just a manual dashboard.",
      "sourceLabel": "PayPal Developer Docs",
      "sourceUrl": "https://developer.paypal.com/docs/invoicing/",
      "submitter": "G2 research",
      "status": "accepted",
      "sourceNote": "Official PayPal developer documentation.",
      "article": "PayPal's [Invoicing API documentation](https://developer.paypal.com/docs/invoicing/) now presents create, send, manage, reminder, and refund flows as a developer-facing invoicing surface.\n\nFor buyers, this reframes PayPal Invoicing as more than a manual invoice dashboard. A software company or platform can evaluate PayPal as an embeddable invoicing layer, especially when the workflow needs to live inside an existing product experience rather than a separate finance tool.\n\n- Buyer signal: Relevant for teams that need API-backed invoicing but do not need a full subscription billing suite.\n- Follow-up: Verify API coverage for invoice lifecycle events, reminders, partial payments, refunds, webhooks, reconciliation, and accounting exports.",
      "productSlug": "paypal-invoicing",
      "productTitle": "PayPal Invoicing",
